  <!-- 01 THESIS -->
  <section id="thesis"><div class="wrap">
    <div class="sec-head reveal"><div class="sec-num" data-pat="0"></div><div class="txt">
      <span class="eyebrow">01 — The idea</span>
      <h2 class="h2">Let the software make the first call.</h2>
      <p class="lead sec-sub">A farm produces an enormous amount of data. Soil probes, weather feeds, crop-health scans, all day long. A normal dashboard hands all of that to the grower and expects them to make sense of it. I didn't want to add another panel to the pile. I wanted the software to read the data and say, in plain terms, what it would do and why.</p>
    </div></div>
    <div class="thesis reveal">
      <div class="big">Reading the data is the boring part.<br><span class="hl-g">Deciding is the hard part.</span></div>
      <p class="sub">This turns the usual setup around. The charts stay, but they move into the background. The thing you actually deal with is the Copilot. It knows the farm, it shows its reasoning, and it gets you to a decision quickly.</p>
      <div class="thesis-cards">
        <div><div class="n">The old way</div><h4>Dashboards describe</h4><p>Rows of numbers about what already happened. Making sense of them, and deciding what to do, is left to you.</p></div>
        <div><div class="n">The shift</div><h4>The Copilot suggests</h4><p>The same numbers, turned into a suggestion you can act on. The action sits right next to it.</p></div>
        <div><div class="n">What changes</div><h4>Charts become backup</h4><p>The charts don't go anywhere. They become what the Copilot points to when you ask it "why?"</p></div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div></section>

  <div class="band">
  <!-- 02 THE PROBLEM -->
  <section id="problem"><div class="wrap">
    <div class="sec-head reveal"><div class="sec-num" data-pat="0,1,2"></div><div class="txt">
      <span class="eyebrow">02 — The problem</span>
      <h2 class="h2">The data was all there. The decision wasn't.</h2>
      <p class="lead sec-sub">A lot of farms already have the sensors, the weather feeds, the imagery. Measurement isn't the hard part now. The hard part is the morning routine: sitting with all those readings and working out what actually needs doing before the day runs away from you.</p>
    </div></div>
    <div class="grid-3">
      <div class="card reveal"><div class="ic"><i data-lucide="layers"></i></div><span class="tagsm">01</span><h4 style="margin-top:8px">Everything in a different place</h4><p>Soil in one place, weather in another, disease somewhere else. You put the picture together in your head before you can decide anything.</p></div>
      <div class="card reveal"><div class="ic"><i data-lucide="clock"></i></div><span class="tagsm">02</span><h4 style="margin-top:8px">You saw problems late</h4><p>A dashboard shows you trouble once it's already clear. By then the cheap moment to fix it has usually gone.</p></div>
      <div class="card reveal"><div class="ic"><i data-lucide="eye"></i></div><span class="tagsm">03</span><h4 style="margin-top:8px">A chart doesn't say what to do</h4><p>Seeing that soil moisture dropped tells you something happened. It doesn't tell you whether to water today or wait for rain. That call stayed with the grower.</p></div>
    </div>
  </div></section>
  </div>

  <!-- 03 PRIMARY PERSONA -->
  <section id="persona"><div class="wrap">
    <div class="sec-head reveal"><div class="sec-num" data-pat="0,3,6"></div><div class="txt">
      <span class="eyebrow">03 — Who it’s for</span>
      <h2 class="h2">I designed this for one person in particular.</h2>
      <p class="lead sec-sub">There's no research behind this person, and I want to be honest about that. He's a guess. But I find it easier to design for someone specific than for farmers in general, so I picked a profile and stuck with it. This is roughly who I had in mind. <span style="color:var(--amber)">(Still a guess. I'd want to check it.)</span></p>
    </div></div>
    <div class="persona reveal">
      <div>
        <div class="pav"><img alt="Divyesh Patel, farm manager, standing in his field" src="data:image/jpeg;base64,"></div>
        <div class="pname">Divyesh Patel</div>
        <div class="prole">Farm Manager · Kadod Estate, Surat</div>
        <div class="pquote">“I don’t need more charts. I need to know which field needs me first.”</div>
        <div class="pmeta">
          <div><div class="k">Estate</div><div class="v2">70.2 ha · 6 crop zones · 7 fields</div></div>
          <div><div class="k">Works from</div><div class="v2">Phone in the field · desktop in the ops room</div></div>
          <div><div class="k">Digital comfort</div><div class="pbar"><i style="width:82%"></i></div></div>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div>
        <div class="pgrid">
          <div class="pblock"><div class="h"><span class="ci"><i data-lucide="target"></i></span>Goals</div>
            <ul><li>Get to the field that's in real trouble before it costs him.</li><li>Keep the irrigation and spray crews out of each other's way across seven fields.</li><li>Stay a step ahead of the weather instead of chasing it.</li><li>Finish the season a little ahead of the plan.</li></ul>
          </div>
          <div class="pblock"><div class="h"><span class="ci"><i data-lucide="alert-triangle"></i></span>Frustrations</div>
            <ul><li>What he needs is spread across different apps and tabs.</li><li>Alerts tend to arrive after the easy fix has passed.</li><li>Reading curves takes up the first hour of the day.</li><li>It's hard to separate a real problem from noise.</li></ul>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="pblock pneeds"><div class="h"><span class="ci"><i data-lucide="check"></i></span>What he needs from AgriOS</div>
          <ul><li>A short list of what needs him today, not a screen of numbers.</li><li>Advice he can trust, and check when he wants to.</li><li>A way to act without leaving the screen: start a drip, book a spray, move a crew.</li><li>The full data underneath, for when he feels like digging in.</li></ul>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="scenario reveal">
      <div class="sc-lbl"><i data-lucide="clock"></i>How a morning might go</div>
      <p><b>Quarter to seven.</b> Divyesh opens the app before he's finished his tea. Two fields need him before the rain comes at four. He taps <b>Why?</b> on Kadod South, reads the reasoning, decides it's right, and starts a drip. He books the spray on Riverside and moves a crew. Three decisions before the tea goes cold. That's the whole idea.</p>
    </div>
  </div></section>

  <div class="band">
  <!-- 04 THE DIFFERENCE -->
  <section id="difference"><div class="wrap">
    <div class="sec-head reveal"><div class="sec-num" data-pat="0,1"></div><div class="txt">
      <span class="eyebrow">04 — The difference</span>
      <h2 class="h2">Same data. Two very different answers.</h2>
      <p class="lead sec-sub">Same morning Divyesh just had. One farm, the same readings. Flip between what a normal dashboard would show him and what the Copilot makes of it.</p>
    </div></div>
    <div class="reveal">
      <div class="compare-toggle" role="tablist">
        <button class="active" data-cmp="dash" role="tab"><i data-lucide="layers"></i>Dashboard view</button>
        <button class="cop" data-cmp="cop" role="tab"><i data-lucide="sparkles"></i>Copilot view</button>
      </div>
      <div class="compare-stage" id="cmpStage"></div>
    </div>
  </div></section>
  </div>

  <!-- 05 FRAMING & ASSUMPTIONS -->
  <section id="framing"><div class="wrap">
    <div class="sec-head reveal"><div class="sec-num" data-pat="0,1,2,5,8"></div><div class="txt">
      <span class="eyebrow">05 — Framing &amp; assumptions</span>
      <h2 class="h2">This is a concept, so here's what I'm assuming.</h2>
      <p class="lead sec-sub">I did this on my own, without access to real growers, so none of it is tested. I'd rather say that plainly than pass guesses off as findings. Below is the honest version: the person I designed around (a guess), the constraints I worked inside, and the questions I'd want to ask real people before building anything.</p>
    </div></div>

    <div class="reveal" style="margin-bottom:30px">
      <div style="border:1px solid var(--line);border-left:3px solid var(--amber);border-radius:12px;padding:16px 18px;background:var(--surface);display:flex;gap:12px;align-items:flex-start">
        <span style="color:var(--amber);flex:0 0 auto;margin-top:1px"><i data-lucide="info"></i></span>
        <div style="font-size:14px;color:var(--muted);line-height:1.55"><b style="color:var(--ink)">Where this stands.</b> It's a concept, not something that shipped. The person below is made up, and the impact further down is what I expect rather than what I measured. Both are flagged that way so you can weigh the thinking without me talking it up.</div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="reveal">
      <div class="h" style="font-family:var(--mono);font-size:11px;letter-spacing:.14em;text-transform:uppercase;color:var(--green-2);margin:0 0 16px">Who I pictured (all guesses)</div>
      <div class="grid-3" style="margin-bottom:20px">
        <div class="card">
          <span class="badge b-warn"><i data-lucide="alert-triangle"></i>Assumption</span>
          <h4 style="margin-top:14px">The owner-operator</h4>
          <p style="font-family:var(--mono);font-size:10.5px;letter-spacing:.06em;color:var(--faint);text-transform:uppercase;margin:3px 0 12px">Small acreage · in the field</p>
          <p><b style="color:var(--ink)">Wants</b> to know what to do today, from a phone, on a signal that drops in and out.</p>
          <p style="margin-top:8px"><b style="color:var(--ink)">If I've got this wrong</b>, the whole recommendation-first idea gets shaky.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="card">
          <span class="badge b-warn"><i data-lucide="alert-triangle"></i>Assumption</span>
          <h4 style="margin-top:14px">The farm manager</h4>
          <p style="font-family:var(--mono);font-size:10.5px;letter-spacing:.06em;color:var(--faint);text-transform:uppercase;margin:3px 0 12px">Multi-field · desk + field</p>
          <p><b style="color:var(--ink)">Has</b> a lot of blocks to watch, plus crews and irrigation to line up.</p>
          <p style="margin-top:8px"><b style="color:var(--ink)">If I've got this wrong</b>, the map and the multi-field view stop earning their place.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="card">
          <span class="badge b-warn"><i data-lucide="alert-triangle"></i>Assumption</span>
          <h4 style="margin-top:14px">The agronomist</h4>
          <p style="font-family:var(--mono);font-size:10.5px;letter-spacing:.06em;color:var(--faint);text-transform:uppercase;margin:3px 0 12px">Advisor · trusts raw data</p>
          <p><b style="color:var(--ink)">Wants</b> the raw curves, and gets wary the moment something's been simplified for him.</p>
          <p style="margin-top:8px"><b style="color:var(--ink)">If I've got this wrong</b>, pushing the dashboard to the background just irritates the expert.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="grid-2" style="margin-top:16px;align-items:start">
      <div class="card reveal">
        <div class="h" style="font-family:var(--mono);font-size:11px;letter-spacing:.14em;text-transform:uppercase;color:var(--green-2);margin-bottom:6px">Rules I set for myself</div>
        <div class="impact-item"><span class="ci" style="color:var(--green-deep)"><i data-lucide="wifi"></i></span><div class="t"><b>Patchy signal.</b> I kept the views light and offline-first instead of leaning on heavy maps.</div></div>
        <div class="impact-item"><span class="ci" style="color:var(--green-deep)"><i data-lucide="cpu"></i></span><div class="t"><b>Flaky sensors.</b> If a reading is old or shaky, the screen says so rather than hiding it.</div></div>
        <div class="impact-item"><span class="ci" style="color:var(--green-deep)"><i data-lucide="eye"></i></span><div class="t"><b>Nobody trusts a black box.</b> Every suggestion can be opened up and traced back to real readings.</div></div>
        <div class="impact-item"><span class="ci" style="color:var(--green-deep)"><i data-lucide="clock"></i></span><div class="t"><b>Timing matters on a farm.</b> Advice is tied to the window where doing something still changes the outcome.</div></div>
        <div class="impact-item"><span class="ci" style="color:var(--green-deep)"><i data-lucide="alert-triangle"></i></span><div class="t"><b>A bad call can cost a crop.</b> So the Copilot stays cautious, and leans toward things you can undo.</div></div>
      </div>
      <div class="card reveal">
        <div class="h" style="font-family:var(--mono);font-size:11px;letter-spacing:.14em;text-transform:uppercase;color:var(--green-2);margin-bottom:14px">The questions I'd test first</div>
        <ol class="vol">
          <li>Do growers actually trust a recommendation more than a chart, or does it make them nervous?</li>
          <li>Does anyone tap "Why?", and if they do, does it change what they decide?</li>
          <li>Are three health states enough, or do experts want the actual numbers on each block?</li>
          <li>Would anyone let the Copilot act on its own, and if so, inside what limits?</li>
        </ol>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div></section>

  <div class="band">
